Apple Earnings
--------------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-aapl-q3-e=
arnings-report-2023-46673f8f ) :

Apple said revenue declined for the third consecutive quarter, the company=
=E2=80=99s most prolonged sales slump since 2016 as the iPhone-maker contin=
ued to deal with declining demand for consumer devices. Overall iPhone reve=
nue, generally a primary driver of Apple=E2=80=99s profits, missed estimate=
s and fell compared with last year, but Chief Executive Tim Cook highlighte=
d strong sales in emerging markets.

The Cupertino, Calif.-based tech giant posted sales of $81.8 billion for th=
e quarter ended in July, down 1.4% from the prior year but largely in line =
with analyst estimates. Net income was up 2.3% annually at $19.9 billion. T=
he company=E2=80=99s all-important iPhone sales fell 2.4% to $39.7 billion,=
 missing analysts expectations of $40.2 billion in iPhone revenue.

Apple said revenue in its services unit reached a new all-time high of $21 =
billion, driven by more than one billion paid subscriptions to offerings su=
ch as streaming music, TV products or spending software in the App Store.

This was an incredibly boring set of earnings, and frankly, that=E2=80=99s =
to Apple=E2=80=99s credit. Yes, iPhone sales were disappointing, but as Coo=
k noted on the call ( https://seekingalpha.com/article/4623702-apple-inc-aa=
pl-q3-2023-earnings-call-transcript ) , Apple actually took share in market=
s like the United States where smartphone sales have plummeted. The key for=
 Apple is that their primary challenge in terms of sales is elongated upgra=
de cycles; iPhone users aren=E2=80=99t leaving the platform, while the comp=
any is still attracting switchers. To that end, Apple actually grew iPhone =
sales in Europe and China, both of which are majority Android.

That points to the real hero of these earnings: Services. Apple hit a new a=
ll-time high in terms of its installed base (again, no one is leaving the i=
Phone, they=E2=80=99re just putting off buying new ones), and that is leadi=
ng to continued robust Services growth =E2=80=94 8% year-over-year. It=E2=
=80=99s worth calling this out, particularly for those of us who have frett=
ed about Apple=E2=80=99s Services push detracting from its product focus: t=
his quarter is one of the best possible counter-arguments, because Services=
 gives space =E2=80=94 at least from an investor perspective =E2=80=94 for =
Apple to focus on products, even if their core market is in a bit of a slum=
p.

One other interesting Services-related note: a side effect of a down quarte=
r for products alongside continued Services growth is sky-high gross margin=
s =E2=80=94 44.5% in this case. Services of course have much higher margins=
 than products, but the fact that the overall market for smartphones is slu=
mping helps Apple=E2=80=99s product margins too, because components are a l=
ot cheaper. This is, it must be said, a pretty compelling trick if you can =
pull it off: it=E2=80=99s basically built-in that slowing top-line growth f=
or Apple means increased profitability.

OpenAI, GPTBot, and Robots.txt
------------------------------

From The Verge ( https://www.theverge.com/2023/8/7/23823046/openai-data-scr=
ape-block-ai ) :

OpenAI now lets you block its web crawler from scraping your site to help t=
rain GPT models. OpenAI said website operators can specifically disallow it=
s GPTBot crawler on their site=E2=80=99s Robots.txt file or block its IP ad=
dress. =E2=80=9CWeb pages crawled with the GPTBot user agent may potentiall=
y be used to improve future models and are filtered to remove sources that =
require paywall access, are known to gather personally identifiable informa=
tion (PII), or have text that violates our policies,=E2=80=9D OpenAI said i=
n the blog post. For sources that don=E2=80=99t fit the excluded criteria, =
=E2=80=9Callowing GPTBot to access your site can help AI models become more=
 accurate and improve their general capabilities and safety.=E2=80=9D

Blocking the GPTBot may be the first step in OpenAI allowing internet users=
 to opt out of having their data used for training its large language model=
s. It follows some early attempts at creating a flag that would exclude con=
tent from training, like a =E2=80=9CNoAI=E2=80=9D tag conceived by DeviantA=
rt last year. It does not retroactively remove content previously scraped f=
rom a site from ChatGPT=E2=80=99s training data.

My initial reaction to this news is honestly pretty cynical, and that last =
line explains why: OpenAI has already benefited from all of the data on the=
 Internet, and establishing a norm that sites can opt out of future AI mode=
ls cements the advantage of being a first mover. Keep in mind that it=E2=80=
=99s not at all clear that crawling Internet data is in any way illegal; I =
think there is a strong case ( https://stratechery.com/2023/fair-use-and-mo=
del-training-getty-images-vs-stable-diffusion-adobes-regulatory-capture-bet=
